content.title: Star Trek: Strange New Worlds

textRecommendations.headline: Enjoy this optimistic entry point into the alien worlds of Stark Trek
textRecommendations.body: “I think that Star Trek is an important show for anyone to watch, in terms of the way that it promotes a sense of hopefulness and optimism for the future. If you’re not familiar with Star Trek, “Strange New Worlds” is the perfect gateway series to start with, except maybe the original series. It’s a mission-of-the-week show, and you don’t need much background on Star Trek to watch it. It’s a great starting point that appeals to many generations, a great show for kids to watch with parents and grandparents.”

profile.bio: It may be hard to recognize Rebecca Romijn from one of her most iconic roles because she starred as the blue mutant Mystique in “X-Men” (2000), “X2” (2003), and “X-Men: The Last Stand” (2006). She took the lead role opposite Antonio Banderas in the cult classic “Femme Fatale” (2002) and played alongside Greg Kinnear and Robert De Niro in “Godsend” (2004). Despite a few appearances on the small screen before, her first major television role came with “Ugly Betty” (2006–2008) where she starred as Alexis Meade. She was first cast as Number One/Una Chin-Riley in “Star Trek: Discovery” (2019) before reprising the role for “Star Trek: Strange New Worlds” (2022–).

textRecommendations.headline: The perfect Star Trek starting point for beginners
textRecommendations.body: With a fictional space as grand as the Star Trek universe, it can be overwhelming trying to find a place to start and catch up. But Strange New Worlds is the perfect beginning as it was for me, a non-Trekkie who found herself diving deep and, surprisingly, following along seamlessly. The anthology format makes it easy to step into this world without expansive knowledge of the lore, and it makes it effortless to appreciate the characters as they are. With an incredibly fantastic cast, excellent writing, and gorgeous directing, every episode is a thrilling ride.

profile.bio:
Gissane (pronounced geese-enny) is a romance enthusiast who's taken her Master's degree in English and love for essays into writing lengthy analyses about pop culture. She is the founder and Editor-in-Chief of Lady Geeks Media. She's a Tomatometer-Approved critic. When she isn't writing about pop culture, she can be found writing and reading romance novels.

Experience and Education

While completing her Bachelor’s in creative writing and Master’s in English literature, Gissane has been working in the industry for over ten years, covering a wide range of TV shows and movies, while writing romance novels since the pandemic began. Formerly, Gissane was the lead TV editor at CBR, and now, along with JustWatch, she contributes to Fangirlish. 

Favorite Movies and TV Shows

Picking a favorite movie or a TV show is always the hardest, but classics like Roman Holiday, It’s a Wonderful Life, and Moulin Rouge are a huge reason for the type of critic Gissane has chosen to become. She’ll often vocalize that Mamma Mia! Here We Go Again is better than the original, and Pride and Prejudice (2005) is essential viewing for all, not just romance fans. As for TV shows, Ted Lasso will always hold a special place in her heart as well as Parks and Recreation. She’s also a big fan of most Star Wars properties (Obi-Wan Kenobi, in particular) and will run far, far away from horror because she’s too scared.
